[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] This document describes the lexis, the syntax, and the semantics of the Nim language.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] To learn how to compile Nim programs and generate documentation see the Compiler User Guide and the DocGen Tools Guide.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The language constructs are explained using an extended BNF, in which (a)* means 0 or more a's, a+ means 1 or more a's, and (a)? means an optional *a*.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Parentheses may be used to group elements.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] & is the lookahead operator; &a means that an a is expected but not consumed.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] It will be consumed in the following rule.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The |, / symbols are used to mark alternatives and have the lowest precedence. / is the ordered choice that requires the parser to try the alternatives in the given order. / is often used to ensure the grammar is not ambiguous.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Non-terminals start with a lowercase letter, abstract terminal symbols are in UPPERCASE.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Verbatim terminal symbols (including keywords) are quoted with '.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The binary ^* operator is used as a shorthand for 0 or more occurrences separated by its second argument; likewise ^+ means 1 or more occurrences: a ^+ b is short for a (b a)* and a ^* b is short for (a (b a)*)?.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Other parts of Nim, like scoping rules or runtime semantics, are described informally.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Nim code specifies a computation that acts on a memory consisting of components called locations.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] A variable is basically a name for a location.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Each variable and location is of a certain type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The variable's type is called static type, the location's type is called dynamic type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] If the static type is not the same as the dynamic type, it is a super-type or subtype of the dynamic type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] An identifier is a symbol declared as a name for a variable, type, procedure, etc.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The region of the program over which a declaration applies is called the scope of the declaration.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The meaning of an identifier is determined by the smallest enclosing scope in which the identifier is declared unless overloading resolution rules suggest otherwise.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] An expression specifies a computation that produces a value or location.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Expressions that produce locations are called l-values.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] An l-value can denote either a location or the value the location contains, depending on the context.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] A Nim program consists of one or more text source files containing Nim code.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] It is processed by a Nim compiler into an executable.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The nature of this executable depends on the compiler implementation; it may, for example, be a native binary or JavaScript source code.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] In a typical Nim program, most of the code is compiled into the executable.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] However, some code may be executed at compile-time.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] This can include constant expressions, macro definitions, and Nim procedures used by macro definitions.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Most of the Nim language is supported at compile-time, but there are some restrictions -- see Restrictions on Compile-Time Execution for details.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] We use the term runtime to cover both compile-time execution and code execution in the executable.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The compiler parses Nim source code into an internal data structure called the abstract syntax tree (AST).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Then, before executing the code or compiling it into the executable, it transforms the AST through semantic analysis.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] This adds semantic information such as expression types, identifier meanings, and in some cases expression values.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] An error detected during semantic analysis is called a static error.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Errors described in this manual are static errors when not otherwise specified.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] A panic is an error that the implementation detects and reports at runtime.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The method for reporting such errors is via *raising exceptions* or *dying with a fatal error*.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] However, the implementation provides a means to disable these runtime checks.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Whether a panic results in an exception or in a fatal error is implementation specific.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Thus, the following program is invalid; even though the code purports to catch the IndexDefect from an out-of-bounds array access, the compiler may instead choose to allow the program to die with a fatal error.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The current implementation allows switching between these different behaviors via --panics:on|off.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] When panics are turned on, the program dies with a panic, if they are turned off the runtime errors are turned into exceptions.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The benefit of --panics:on is that it produces smaller binary code and the compiler has more freedom to optimize the code.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] An unchecked runtime error is an error that is not guaranteed to be detected and can cause the subsequent behavior of the computation to be arbitrary.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Unchecked runtime errors cannot occur if only safe language features are used and if no runtime checks are disabled.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] A constant expression is an expression whose value can be computed during a semantic analysis of the code in which it appears.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] It is never an l-value and never has side effects.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Constant expressions are not limited to the capabilities of semantic analysis, such as constant folding; they can use all Nim language features that are supported for compile-time execution.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Since constant expressions can be used as an input to semantic analysis (such as for defining array bounds), this flexibility requires the compiler to interleave semantic analysis and compile-time code execution.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] It is mostly accurate to picture semantic analysis proceeding top to bottom and left to right in the source code, with compile-time code execution interleaved when necessary to compute values that are required for subsequent semantic analysis.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] We will see much later in this document that macro invocation not only requires this interleaving, but also creates a situation where semantic analysis does not entirely proceed top to bottom and left to right.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] All Nim source files are in the UTF-8 encoding (or its ASCII subset).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Any of the standard platform line termination sequences can be used - the Unix form using ASCII LF (linefeed), the Windows form using the ASCII sequence CR LF (return followed by linefeed), or the old Macintosh form using the ASCII CR (return) character.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] All of these forms can be used equally, regardless of the platform.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Nim's standard grammar describes an indentation sensitive language.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] This means that all the control structures are recognized by indentation.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Indentation consists only of spaces; tabulators are not allowed.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The indentation handling is implemented as follows: The lexer annotates the following token with the preceding number of spaces; indentation is not a separate token.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] This trick allows parsing of Nim with only 1 token of lookahead.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The parser uses a stack of indentation levels: the stack consists of integers counting the spaces.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The indentation information is queried at strategic places in the parser but ignored otherwise: The pseudo-terminal IND{>} denotes an indentation that consists of more spaces than the entry at the top of the stack; IND{=} an indentation that has the same number of spaces.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] DED is another pseudo terminal that describes the *action* of popping a value from the stack, IND{>} then implies to push onto the stack.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Comments start anywhere outside a string or character literal with the hash character .
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Comments consist of a concatenation of .
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] A comment piece starts with and runs until the end of the line.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The end of line characters belong to the piece.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Documentation comments are tokens; they are only allowed at certain places in the input file as they belong to the syntax tree.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Starting with version 0.13.0 of the language Nim supports multiline comments.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] This was how multiline comments were done before version 0.13.0, and it is used to provide specifications to testament test framework.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Currently, any Unicode character with an ordinal value > 127 (non-ASCII) is classified as a letter and may thus be part of an identifier but later versions of the language may assign some Unicode characters to belong to the operator characters instead.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Some keywords are unused; they are reserved for future developments of the language.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] That means only the first letters are compared in a case-sensitive manner.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Other letters are compared case-insensitively within the ASCII range and underscores are ignored.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] It allows programmers to mostly use their own preferred spelling style, be it humpStyle or snake_style, and libraries written by different programmers cannot use incompatible conventions.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] A Nim-aware editor or IDE can show the identifiers as preferred.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Another advantage is that it frees the programmer from remembering the exact spelling of an identifier.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The exception with respect to the first letter allows common code like var foo: Foo to be parsed unambiguously.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Note that this rule also applies to keywords, meaning that notin is the same as notIn and not_in (all-lowercase version (notin, isnot) is the preferred way of writing keywords).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Historically, Nim was a fully style-insensitive language.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] This meant that it was not case-sensitive and underscores were ignored and there was not even a distinction between foo and Foo.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] If a keyword is enclosed in backticks it loses its keyword property and becomes an ordinary identifier.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Terminal symbol in the grammar: STR_LIT.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Strings in Nim may contain any 8-bit value, even embedded zeros.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] However, some operations may interpret the first binary zero as a terminator.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Terminal symbol in the grammar: TRIPLESTR_LIT.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] String literals can also be delimited by three double quotes """ ...
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Literals in this form may run for several lines, may contain " and do not interpret any escape sequences.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] For convenience, when the opening """ is followed by a newline (there may be whitespace between the opening """ and the newline), the newline (and the preceding whitespace) is not included in the string.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Terminal symbol in the grammar: RSTR_LIT.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] There are also raw string literals that are preceded with the letter r (or R) and are delimited by matching double quotes (just like ordinary string literals) and do not interpret the escape sequences.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] r"""" is not possible with this notation, because the three leading quotes introduce a triple quoted string literal. r""" is the same as """ since triple quoted string literals do not interpret escape sequences either.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Terminal symbols in the grammar: GENERALIZED_STR_LIT, GENERALIZED_TRIPLESTR_LIT.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The construct identifier"string literal" (without whitespace between the identifier and the opening quotation mark) is a generalized raw string literal.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] It is a shortcut for the construct identifier(r"string literal"), so it denotes a routine call with a raw string literal as its only argument.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Generalized raw string literals are especially convenient for embedding mini languages directly into Nim (for example regular expressions).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The construct identifier"""string literal""" exists too.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] It is a shortcut for identifier("""string literal""").
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Character literals are enclosed in single quotes '' and can contain the same escape sequences as strings - with one exception: the platform dependent newline (\p) is not allowed as it may be wider than one character (it can be the pair CR/LF).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] A character is not a Unicode character but a single byte.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Rationale: It enables the efficient support of array[char, int] or set[char].
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The Rune type can represent any Unicode character.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] A character literal that does not end in ' is interpreted as ' if there is a preceding backtick token.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] There must be no whitespace between the preceding backtick token and the character literal.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] This special case ensures that a declaration like proc `'customLiteral`(s: string) is valid. proc `'customLiteral`(s: string) is the same as proc `'\''customLiteral`(s: string).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] As can be seen in the productions, numeric literals can contain underscores for readability.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Integer and floating-point literals may be given in decimal (no prefix), binary (prefix 0b), octal (prefix 0o), and hexadecimal (prefix 0x) notation.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The fact that the unary minus - in a number literal like -1 is considered to be part of the literal is a late addition to the language.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The rationale is that an expression -128'i8 should be valid and without this special case, this would be impossible -- 128 is not a valid int8 value, only -128 is.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] For the unary_minus rule there are further restrictions that are not covered in the formal grammar.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] For - to be part of the number literal the immediately preceding character has to be in the set {' ', '\t', '\n', '\r', ',', ';', '(', '[', '{'}.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] This set was designed to cover most cases in a natural manner.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The suffix starting with an apostrophe (''') is called a type suffix.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Literals without a type suffix are of an integer type unless the literal contains a dot or E|e in which case it is of type float.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] This integer type is int if the literal is in the range low(int32)..high(int32), otherwise it is int64.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] For notational convenience, the apostrophe of a type suffix is optional if it is not ambiguous (only hexadecimal floating-point literals with a type suffix can be ambiguous).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Literals must match the datatype, for example, 333'i8 is an invalid literal.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Non-base-10 literals are used mainly for flags and bit pattern representations, therefore the checking is done on bit width and not on value range.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] If the suffix is not predefined, then the suffix is assumed to be a call to a proc, template, macro or other callable identifier that is passed the string containing the literal.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] More formally, a custom numeric literal 123'custom is transformed to r"123".'custom in the parsing step.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] There is no AST node kind that corresponds to this transformation.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Custom numeric literals are covered by the grammar rule named CUSTOM_NUMERIC_LIT.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] A custom numeric literal is a single token.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] These keywords are also operators: and or not xor shl shr div mod in notin is isnot of as from.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] ., =, :, :: are not available as general operators; they are used for other notational purposes.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The not keyword is always a unary operator, a not b is parsed as a(not b), not as (a) not (b).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Unicode operators can be combined with non-Unicode operator symbols.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The usual precedence extensions then apply, for example, ⊠= is an assignment like operator just like *= is.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] No Unicode normalization step is performed.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] The slice operator .. takes precedence over other tokens that contain a dot: {..} are the three tokens {, .., } and not the two tokens {., .}.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] This section lists Nim's standard syntax.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] How the parser handles the indentation is already described in the Lexical Analysis section.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Binary operators have 11 different levels of precedence.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Binary operators whose first character is ^ are right-associative, all other binary operators are left-associative.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Unary operators always bind stronger than any binary operator: $a + b is ($a) + b and not $(a + b).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] If a unary operator's first character is @ it is a sigil-like operator which binds stronger than a primarySuffix: @x.abc is parsed as (@x).abc whereas $x.abc is parsed as $(x.abc).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Operators ending in either ->, ~> or => are called arrow like, and have the lowest precedence of all operators.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] If the operator ends with = and its first character is none of <, >, !, =, ~, ?, it is an *assignment operator* which has the second-lowest precedence.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Otherwise, precedence is determined by the first character.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Terminal symbol in the grammar: DOTLIKEOP.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p01] Dot-like operators are operators starting with ., but not with .., for e.g. .?; they have the same precedence as ., so that a.?b.c is parsed as (a.?b).c instead of a.?(b.c).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] simpleExpr = arrowExpr (OP0 optInd arrowExpr)* pragma?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] exprColonEqExprList = exprColonEqExpr (comma exprColonEqExpr)* (comma)?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] qualifiedIdent = symbol ('.' optInd symbolOrKeyword)?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] identVisDot = symbol '.' optInd symbolOrKeyword OPR?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] identWithPragmaDot = identVisDot pragma?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] declColonEquals = identWithPragma (comma identWithPragma)* comma?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] identColonEquals = IDENT (comma IDENT)* comma?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] routineExpr = ('proc' | 'func' | 'iterator') paramListColon pragma?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] routineType = ('proc' | 'iterator') paramListColon pragma?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] primary = simplePrimary (commandStart expr (doBlock extraPostExprBlock*)?)?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] typeDescExpr = (routineType / simpleExpr) ('not' primary)?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] / simplePrimary (exprEqExpr ^+ comma) postExprBlocks?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] genericParam = symbol (comma symbol)* (colon expr)?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] indAndComment = (IND{>} COMMENT)? | COMMENT?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] routine = optInd identVis pattern? genericParamList?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] objectWhen = 'when' expr colcom objectPart COMMENT?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] objectCase = 'case' (declColonEquals / pragma)?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] conceptDecl = 'concept' conceptParam ^* ',' (pragma)?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] varTupleLhs = '(' optInd (identWithPragma / varTupleLhs) ^+ comma optPar ')' (':' optInd typeDescExpr)?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] constant = (varTuple / identWithPragma) (colon typeDesc)?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] pragmaStmt = pragma (':' COMMENT? stmt)?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] In the example, res and remainder are var parameters.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] Var parameters can be modified by the procedure and the changes are visible to the caller.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] The argument passed to a var parameter has to be an l-value.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] Var parameters are implemented as hidden pointers.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] In the examples, var parameters or pointers are used to provide two return values.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] In the standard library every name of a routine that returns a var type starts with the prefix m per convention.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] In other words, the lifetime of what result points to is attached to the lifetime of the first parameter and that is enough knowledge to verify memory safety at the call site.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] Here var T from container explicitly exposes that the location is derived from the second parameter (called 'container' in this case).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] The syntax var T from p specifies a type varTy[T, 2] which is incompatible with varTy[T, 1].
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] The return value is represented inside the body of a routine as the special result variable.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] This allows for a mechanism much like C++'s "named return value optimization" (NRVO).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] NRVO means that the stores to result inside p directly affect the destination dest in let/var dest = p(args) (definition of dest) and also in dest = p(args) (assignment to dest).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] This is achieved by rewriting dest = p(args) to p'(args, dest) where p' is a variation of p that returns void and receives a hidden mutable parameter representing result.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] NRVO applies for T if sizeof(T) >= N (where N is implementation dependent), in other words, it applies for "big" structures.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] If p can raise an exception, NRVO applies regardless.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] The compiler can produce a warning in these cases, however this behavior is turned off by default.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] It can be enabled for a section of code via the warning[ObservableStores] and push/pop pragmas.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] The [] subscript operator for arrays/openarrays/sequences can be overloaded for any type (with some exceptions) by defining a routine with the name [].
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] Assignment to subscripts can also be overloaded by naming a routine []=, which has precedence over assigning to the result of [].
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] Overloads of the subscript operator cannot be applied to routine or type symbols themselves, as this conflicts with the syntax for instantiating generic parameters, i.e. foo[int](1, 2, 3) or Foo[int].
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] For dynamic dispatch to work on an object it should be a reference type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p02] In the example the constructors newLit and newPlus are procs because they should use static binding, but eval is a method because it requires dynamic binding.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] As can be seen in the example, base methods have to be annotated with the base pragma.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The base pragma also acts as a reminder for the programmer that a base method m is used as the foundation to determine all the effects that a call to m might cause.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Dynamic method resolution can be inhibited via the builtin system.procCall.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] This is somewhat comparable to the super keyword that traditional OOP languages offer.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The for statement is an abstract mechanism to iterate over the elements of a container.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Like while statements, for statements open an implicit block so that they can be left with a break statement.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The for loop declares iteration variables - their scope reaches until the end of the loop body.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The iteration variables' types are inferred by the return type of the iterator.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] An iterator is similar to a procedure, except that it can be called in the context of a for loop.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Iterators provide a way to specify the iteration over an abstract type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The yield statement in the called iterator plays a key role in the execution of a for loop.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Whenever a yield statement is reached, the data is bound to the for loop variables and control continues in the body of the for loop.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The iterator's local variables and execution state are automatically saved between calls.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] If the iterator yields a tuple, there can be as many iteration variables as there are components in the tuple.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The i'th iteration variable's type is the type of the i'th component.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] In other words, implicit tuple unpacking in a for loop context is supported.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] If the for loop has exactly 2 variables, a pairs iterator is implicitly invoked.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Symbol lookup of the identifiers items/pairs is performed after the rewriting step, so that all overloads of items/pairs are taken into account.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] There are 2 kinds of iterators in Nim: *inline* and *closure* iterators.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] An inline iterator is an iterator that's always inlined by the compiler leading to zero overhead for the abstraction, but may result in a heavy increase in code size.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Caution: the body of a for loop over an inline iterator is inlined into each yield statement appearing in the iterator code, so ideally the code should be refactored to contain a single yield when possible to avoid code bloat.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Inline iterators are second class citizens; They can be passed as parameters only to other inlining code facilities like templates, macros, and other inline iterators.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] 2. return is allowed in a closure iterator but not in an inline iterator (but rarely useful) and ends the iteration.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Neither inline nor closure iterators have the special result variable.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Iterators that are neither marked {.closure.} nor {.inline.} explicitly default to being inline, but this may change in future versions of the implementation.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The iterator type is always of the calling convention closure implicitly.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Unlike named iterators, anonymous iterator expressions evaluate to the iterator type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] In practice, this means a named iterator declaration without {.closure.} defaults to inline, but an expression like let it = iterator(): int = yield 1 produces a callable closure iterator value.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The builtin system.finished can be used to determine if an iterator has finished its operation; no exception is raised on an attempt to invoke an iterator that has already finished its work.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] It helps to think that the iterator actually returns a pair (value, done) and finished is used to access the hidden done field.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Closure iterators are *resumable functions* and so one has to provide the arguments to every call.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Because of full backend function call apparatus involvement, closure iterator invocation is typically higher cost than inline iterators.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Adornment by a macro wrapper at the call site like this is a possibly useful reminder.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The factory proc, as an ordinary procedure, can be recursive.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The above macro allows such recursion to look much like a recursive iterator would.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] See also iterable for passing iterators to templates and macros.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A converter can also be explicitly invoked for improved readability.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Note that implicit converter chaining is not supported: If there is a converter from type A to type B and from type B to type C, the implicit conversion from A to C is not provided.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A type section begins with the type keyword.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A type definition binds a type to a name.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Type definitions can be recursive or even mutually recursive.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Mutually recursive types are only possible within a single type section.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Nominal types like objects or enums can only be defined in a type section.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The statements after the try are executed in sequential order unless an exception e is raised.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] If the exception type of e matches any listed in an except clause, the corresponding statements are executed.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The statements following the except clauses are called exception handlers.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] If there is a finally clause, it is always executed after the exception handlers.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The exception is *consumed* in an exception handler.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] However, an exception handler may raise another exception.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] If the exception is not handled, it is propagated through the call stack.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] This means that often the rest of the procedure - that is not within a finally clause - is not executed (if an exception occurs).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Note that getCurrentException always returns a ref Exception type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] It is possible to create custom exceptions.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Ending the custom exception's name with Error is recommended.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Instead of a try finally statement a defer statement can be used, which avoids lexical nesting and offers more flexibility in terms of scoping as shown below.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Top-level defer statements are not supported since it's unclear what such a statement should refer to.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Apart from built-in operations like array indexing, memory allocation, etc. the raise statement is the only way to raise an exception.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] If no exception name is given, the current exception is re-raised.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The ReraiseDefect exception is raised if there is no exception to re-raise.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] It follows that the raise statement *always* raises an exception.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The exception tree is defined in the system module.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Every exception inherits from system.Exception.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Exceptions that indicate programming bugs inherit from system.Defect (which is a subtype of Exception) and are strictly speaking not catchable as they can also be mapped to an operation that terminates the whole process.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] If panics are turned into exceptions, these exceptions inherit from Defect.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Exceptions that indicate any other runtime error that can be caught inherit from system.CatchableError (which is a subtype of Exception).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] It is possible to raise/catch imported C++ exceptions.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Types imported using importcpp can be raised or caught.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Exceptions are raised by value and caught by reference.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The raises pragma can be used to explicitly define which exceptions a proc/iterator/method/converter is allowed to raise.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A raises list can also be attached to a proc type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Every expression e of some proc type within a call that is passed to parameter marked as .effectsOf of proc p is assumed to be called indirectly and thus its raises list is added to p's raises list.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Every call to a proc q which has an unknown body (due to a forward declaration) is assumed to raise system.Exception unless q has an explicit raises list.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Procs that are importc'ed are assumed to have .raises: [], unless explicitly declared otherwise.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Every call to a method m is assumed to raise system.Exception unless m has an explicit raises list.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] For every other call, the analysis can determine an exact raises list.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] For determining a raises list, the raise and try statements of p are taken into consideration.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Exceptions inheriting from system.Defect are not tracked with the .raises: [] exception tracking mechanism.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] This is more consistent with the built-in operations.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The reason for this is that DivByZeroDefect inherits from Defect and with --panics:on Defects become unrecoverable errors.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] As can be seen from the example, a parameter of type proc (...) can be annotated as .effectsOf.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Such a parameter allows for effect polymorphism: The proc weDontRaiseButMaybeTheCallback raises the exceptions that callback raises.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Exception tracking is part of Nim's effect system.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A tags list - like a raises list - can also be attached to a proc type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The inference for tag tracking is analogous to the inference for exception tracking.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The forbids pragma defines a list of illegal effects - if any statement invokes any of those effects, the compilation will fail.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Unlike with the tags pragma, the parent context - the function which calls other functions with forbidden effects - doesn't inherit the forbidden list of effects.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The noSideEffect pragma is used to mark a proc/iterator that can have only side effects through parameters.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] This means that the proc/iterator only changes locations that are reachable from its parameters and the return value only depends on the parameters.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] If none of its parameters have the type var, ref, ptr, cstring, or proc, then no locations are modified.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] In other words, a routine has no side effects if it does not access a threadlocal or global variable and it does not call any routine that has a side effect.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] It is a static error to mark a proc/iterator to have no side effect if the compiler cannot verify this.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] As a special semantic rule, the built-in debugEcho pretends to be free of side effects so that it can be used for debugging routines marked as noSideEffect.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] When the compiler cannot infer side effects, as is the case for imported functions, one can annotate them with the sideEffect pragma.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] We call a proc p GC safe when it doesn't access any global variable that contains GC'ed memory (string, seq, ref or a closure) either directly or indirectly through a call to a GC unsafe proc.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The gcsafe annotation can be used to mark a proc to be gcsafe, otherwise this property is inferred by the compiler.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Routines that are imported from C are always assumed to be gcsafe.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The effects pragma has been designed to assist the programmer with the effects analysis.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The compiler produces a hint message that IOError can be raised.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] OSError is not listed as it cannot be raised in the branch the effects pragma appears in.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Generics are Nim's means to parametrize procs, iterators or types with type parameters.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Depending on the context, the brackets are used either to introduce type parameters or to instantiate a generic proc, iterator, or type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The T is called a generic type parameter or a type variable.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Let's consider the anatomy of a generic proc to agree on defined terminology.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The use of the word "formal" here is to denote the symbols as they are defined by the programmer, not as they may be at compile time contextually.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Since generics may be instantiated and types bound, we have more than one entity to think about when generics are involved.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The usage of a generic will resolve the formally defined expression into an instance of that expression bound to only concrete types.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A constraint definition may have more than one symbol defined by separating each definition by a ;.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Notice how T is composed of H and the return type of p is defined as H.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] When this generic proc is instantiated H will be bound to a concrete type, thus making T concrete and the return type of p will be bound to the same concrete type used to define H.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Brackets at the site of usage can be used to supply concrete types to instantiate the generic in the same order that the symbols are defined in the constraint.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Alternatively, type bindings may be inferred by the compiler in some situations, allowing for cleaner code.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The is operator is evaluated during semantic analysis to check for type equivalence.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A type class is a special pseudo-type that can be used to match against types in the context of overload resolution or the is operator.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Furthermore, every generic type automatically creates a type class of the same name that will match any instantiation of the generic type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Whilst the syntax of type classes appears to resemble that of ADTs/algebraic data types in ML-like languages, it should be understood that type classes are static constraints to be enforced at type instantiations.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Type classes are not really types in themselves but are instead a system of providing generic "checks" that ultimately *resolve* to some singular type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Type classes do not allow for runtime type dynamism, unlike object variants or methods.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] proc and iterator type classes also accept a calling convention pragma to restrict the calling convention of the matching proc or iterator type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A type class can be used directly as the parameter's type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Procedures utilizing type classes in such a manner are considered to be implicitly generic.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] They will be instantiated once for each unique combination of parameter types used within the program.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] By default, during overload resolution, each named type class will bind to exactly one concrete type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] We call such type classes bind once types.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Alternatively, the distinct type modifier can be applied to the type class to allow each parameter matching the type class to bind to a different type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Such type classes are called bind many types.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Procs written with the implicitly generic style will often need to refer to the type parameters of the matched generic type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A parameter of type typedesc is itself usable as a type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] If it is used as a type, it's the underlying type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The types var T and typedesc[T] cannot be inferred in a generic instantiation.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The symbol binding rules in generics are slightly subtle: There are "open" and "closed" symbols.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A "closed" symbol cannot be re-bound in the instantiation context, an "open" symbol can.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Per default, overloaded symbols are open and every other symbol is closed.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] In the example, the generic `==` for tuples (as defined in the system module) uses the == operators of the tuple's components.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] However, the == for the Index type is defined *after* the == for tuples; yet the example compiles as the instantiation takes the currently defined symbols into account too.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] mixin statements only make sense in templates and generics.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The bind statement is the counterpart to the mixin statement.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] But a bind is rarely useful because symbol binding from the definition scope is the default.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] bind statements only make sense in templates and generics.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] In module B has an init proc from module C in its scope that is not taken into account when genericB is instantiated which leads to the instantiation of genericA.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The solution is to forward these symbols by a bind statement inside genericB.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A template is a simple form of a macro: It is a simple substitution mechanism that operates on Nim's abstract syntax trees.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] It is processed in the semantic pass of the compiler.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The syntax to *invoke* a template is the same as calling a procedure.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] a > b is transformed into b < a. a in b is transformed into contains(b, a). notin and isnot have the obvious meanings.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The "types" of templates can be the symbols untyped, typed or typedesc.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] These are "meta types", they can only be used in certain contexts.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Regular types can be used too; this implies that typed expressions are expected.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] An untyped parameter means that symbol lookups and type resolution is not performed before the expression is passed to the template.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A template where every parameter is untyped is called an immediate template.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] For historical reasons, templates can be explicitly annotated with an immediate pragma and then these templates do not take part in overloading resolution and the parameters' types are *ignored* by the compiler.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Explicit immediate templates are now deprecated.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] In the example, the two writeLine statements are bound to the actions parameter.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Usually, to pass a block of code to a template, the parameter that accepts the block needs to be of type untyped.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The above code fails with the error message that p is not declared.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The reason for this is that the p() body is type-checked before getting passed to the body parameter and type checking in Nim implies symbol lookups.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] However, since a template cannot iterate over varargs, this feature is generally much more useful for macros.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A template is a hygienic macro and so opens a new scope.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] As in generics, symbol binding can be influenced via mixin or bind statements.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] In the example, name is instantiated with myint, so `T name` becomes Tmyint.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A parameter p in a template is even substituted in the expression x.p.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Whether a symbol that is declared in a template is exposed to the instantiation scope is controlled by the inject and gensym pragmas: gensym'ed symbols are not exposed but inject'ed symbols are.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The default for symbols of entity type, var, let and const is gensym.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] For proc, iterator, converter, template, macro, the default is inject, but if a gensym symbol with the same name is defined in the same syntax-level scope, it will be gensym by default.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] This can be overridden by marking the routine as inject.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] To get rid of hygiene in templates, one can use the dirty pragma for a template. inject and gensym have no effect in dirty templates.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] gensym'ed symbols cannot be used as field in the x.field syntax.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Nor can they be used in the ObjectConstruction(field: value) and namedParameterCall(field = value) syntactic constructs.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The expression x in x.f needs to be semantically checked (that means symbol lookup and type checking) before it can be decided that it needs to be rewritten to f(x).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] It is also not possible to use fully qualified identifiers with module symbol in method call syntax.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The order in which the dot operator binds to symbols prohibits this.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] This means that when for some reason a procedure needs a disambiguation through the module name, the call needs to be written in function call syntax.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A macro is a special function that is executed at compile time.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Normally, the input for a macro is an abstract syntax tree (AST) of the code that is passed to it.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The macro can then do transformations on it and return the transformed AST.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] This can be used to add custom language features and implement domain-specific languages.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Macro invocation is a case where semantic analysis does **not** entirely proceed top to bottom and left to right.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] While macros enable advanced compile-time code transformations, they cannot change Nim's syntax.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Else: Use a generic proc/iterator, if possible.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Arguments that are passed to a varargs parameter are wrapped in an array constructor expression.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] This is why debug iterates over all of args's children.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The above debug macro relies on the fact that write, writeLine and stdout are declared in the system module and are thus visible in the instantiating context.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] There is a way to use bound identifiers (aka symbols) instead of using unbound identifiers.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] In this version of debug, the symbols write, writeLine and stdout are already bound and are not looked up again.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] As the example shows, bindSym does work with overloaded symbols implicitly.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Note that the symbol names passed to bindSym have to be constant.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The experimental feature dynamicBindSym (experimental manual) allows this value to be computed dynamically.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Macros can receive of, elif, else, except, finally and do blocks (including their different forms such as do with routine parameters) as arguments if called in statement form.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Macros named `` case `` can provide implementations of case statements for certain types.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] case macros are subject to overload resolution.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The type of the case statement's selector expression is matched against the type of the first argument of the case macro.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Then the complete case statement is passed in place of the argument and the macro is evaluated.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] In other words, the macro needs to transform the full case statement but only the statement's selector expression is used to determine which macro to call.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] For the purposes of code generation, all static parameters are treated as generic parameters - the proc will be compiled separately for each unique supplied value (or combination of values).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Please note that static T is just a syntactic convenience for the underlying generic type static[T].
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The type parameter can be omitted to obtain the type class of all constant expressions.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A more specific type class can be created by instantiating static with another type class.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The compiler will report any failure to evaluate the expression or a possible type mismatch error.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] In many contexts, Nim treats the names of types as regular values.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] These values exist only during the compilation phase, but since all values must have a type, typedesc is considered their special type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] For instance, the type of the symbol int is typedesc[int].
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Just like with regular generic types, when the generic parameter is omitted, typedesc denotes the type class of all types.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] As a syntactic convenience, one can also use typedesc as a modifier.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Procs featuring typedesc parameters are considered implicitly generic.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] When multiple type parameters are present, they will bind freely to different types.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Overload resolution can be further influenced by constraining the set of types that will match the type parameter.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] This works in practice by attaching attributes to types via templates.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The constraint can be a concrete type or a type class.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] ", isNumber(int) echo "is float a number?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] ", isNumber(float) echo "is RootObj a number?
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Passing typedesc is almost identical, just with the difference that the macro is not instantiated generically.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The type expression is simply passed as a NimNode to the macro, like everything else.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Nim supports splitting a program into pieces by a module concept.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Each module needs to be in its own file and has its own namespace.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Modules enable information hiding and separate compilation.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A module may gain access to the symbols of another module by the import statement.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Recursive module dependencies are allowed, but are slightly subtle.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] Only top-level symbols that are marked with an asterisk (*) are exported.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] A valid module name can only be a valid Nim identifier (and thus its filename is identifier.nim).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] It is not checked that the except list is really exported from the module.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] This feature allows us to compile against different versions of the module, even when one version does not export some of these identifiers.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The import statement is only allowed at the top level.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] String literals can be used for import/include statements.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The compiler performs path substitution when used.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The include statement does something fundamentally different than importing a module: it merely includes the contents of a file.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p03] The syntax import dir / [moduleA, moduleB] can be used to import multiple modules from the same directory.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Path names are syntactically either Nim identifiers or string literals.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] A directory can also be a so-called "pseudo directory".
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] They can be used to avoid ambiguity when there are multiple modules with the same path.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] 2. pkg: The pkg pseudo directory is used to unambiguously refer to a Nimble package.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] However, for technical details that lie outside the scope of this document, its semantics are: *Use the search path to look for module name but ignore the standard library locations*.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] In other words, it is the opposite of std.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] It is recommended and preferred but not currently enforced that all stdlib module imports include the std/ "pseudo directory" as part of the import name.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] It's also possible to use from module import nil if one wants to import the module but wants to enforce fully qualified access to every symbol in module.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] When the exported symbol is another module, all of its definitions will be forwarded.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] One can use an except list to exclude some of the symbols.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Identifiers are valid from the point of their declaration until the end of the block in which the declaration occurred.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The range where the identifier is known is the scope of the identifier.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The exact scope of an identifier depends on the way it was declared.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The *scope* of a variable declared in the declaration part of a block is valid from the point of declaration until the end of the block.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] If a block contains a second block, in which the identifier is redeclared, then inside this block, the second declaration will be valid.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Upon leaving the inner block, the first declaration is valid again.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] An identifier cannot be redefined in the same block, except if valid for procedure or iterator overloading purposes.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] All identifiers of a module are valid from the point of declaration until the end of the module.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Identifiers from indirectly dependent modules are *not* available.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The system module is automatically imported in every module.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Modules can share their name, however, when trying to qualify an identifier with the module name the compiler will fail with ambiguous identifier error.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] One can qualify the identifier by aliasing the module.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] A collection of modules in a file tree with an identifier.nimble file in the root of the tree is called a Nimble package.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] A valid package name can only be a valid Nim identifier and thus its filename is identifier.nimble where identifier is the desired package name.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] A module without a .nimble file is assigned the package identifier: unknown.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The distinction between packages allows diagnostic compiler messages to be scoped to the current project's package vs foreign packages.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The Nim compiler emits different kinds of messages: hint, warning, and error messages.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] An *error* message is emitted if the compiler encounters any static error.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Pragmas are Nim's method to give the compiler additional information / commands without introducing a massive number of new keywords.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Pragmas are processed on the fly during semantic checking.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Pragmas are enclosed in the special {. and .} curly brackets.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Pragmas are also often used as a first implementation to play with a language feature before a nicer syntax to access the feature becomes available.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] This pragma can also take in an optional warning string to relay to developers.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The compileTime pragma is used to mark a proc or variable to be used only during compile-time execution.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Compile-time procs are useful as helpers for macros.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] compileTime variables are available at runtime too.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The noreturn pragma is used to mark a proc that never returns.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The acyclic pragma can be used for object types to mark them as acyclic even though they seem to be cyclic.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] In the example, a tree structure is declared with the Node type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Note that the type definition is recursive and the GC has to assume that objects of this type may form a cyclic graph.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The acyclic pragma passes the information that this cannot happen to the GC.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] If the programmer uses the acyclic pragma for data types that are in reality cyclic, this may result in memory leaks, but memory safety is preserved.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The final pragma can be used for an object type to specify that it cannot be inherited from.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Note that inheritance is only available for objects that inherit from an existing object (via the object of SuperType syntax) or that have been marked as inheritable.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The shallow pragma affects the semantics of a type: The compiler is allowed to make a shallow copy.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] This can cause serious semantic issues and break memory safety!
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] However, it can speed up assignments considerably, because the semantics of Nim require deep copying of sequences and strings.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] An object type can be marked with the pure pragma so that its type field which is used for runtime type identification is omitted.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] This used to be necessary for binary compatibility with other compiled languages.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Then access of its fields always requires full qualification.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] A proc can be marked with the asmNoStackFrame pragma to tell the compiler it should not generate a stack frame for the proc.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] There are also no exit statements like return result; generated and the generated C function is declared as __declspec(naked) or __attribute__((naked)) (depending on the used C compiler).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The error pragma is used to make the compiler output an error message with the given content.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The compilation does not necessarily abort after an error though.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The error pragma can also be used to annotate a symbol (like an iterator or proc).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The *usage* of the symbol then triggers a static error.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The fatal pragma is used to make the compiler output an error message with the given content.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] In contrast to the error pragma, the compilation is guaranteed to be aborted by this pragma.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The warning pragma is used to make the compiler output a warning message with the given content.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Compilation continues after the warning.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The hint pragma is used to make the compiler output a hint message with the given content.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] If the line pragma is used with a parameter, the parameter needs to be a tuple[filename: string, line: int].
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] If it is used without a parameter, system.instantiationInfo() is used.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The linearScanEnd pragma can be used to tell the compiler how to compile a Nim case statement.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] In the example, the case branches 0 and 1 are much more common than the other cases.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Therefore, the generated assembler code should test for these values first so that the CPU's branch predictor has a good chance to succeed (avoiding an expensive CPU pipeline stall).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The other cases might be put into a jump table for O(1) overhead but at the cost of a (very likely) pipeline stall.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The linearScanEnd pragma should be put into the last branch that should be tested against via linear scanning.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] If put into the last branch of the whole case statement, the whole case statement uses linear scanning.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The computedGoto pragma can be used to tell the compiler how to compile a Nim case in a while true statement.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] As the example shows, computedGoto is mostly useful for interpreters.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] If the underlying backend (C compiler) does not support the computed goto extension the pragma is simply ignored.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Redefinition of template symbols with the same signature is allowed.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] This is mostly intended for macro generated code.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The listed pragmas here can be used to override the code generation options for a proc/method/converter.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The implementation currently provides the following possible options (various others may be added later).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The push/pop pragmas are very similar to the option directive, but are used to override the settings temporarily.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] For third party pragmas, it depends on its implementation but uses the same syntax.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The register pragma is for variables only.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] It declares the variable as register, giving the compiler a hint that the variable should be placed in a hardware register for faster access.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] C compilers usually ignore this though and for good reasons: Often they do a better job without it anyway.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] However, in highly specific cases (a dispatch loop of a bytecode interpreter for example) it may provide benefits.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The global pragma can be applied to a variable within a proc to instruct the compiler to store it in a global location and initialize it once at program startup.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] When used within a generic proc, a separate unique global variable will be created for each instantiation of the proc.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The order of initialization of the created global variables within a module is not defined, but all of them will be initialized after any top-level variables in their originating module and before any variable in a module that imports it.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Nim generates some warnings and hints that may annoy the user.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] A mechanism for disabling certain messages is provided: Each hint and warning message is associated with a symbol.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] This is often better than disabling all warnings at once.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Nim produces a warning for symbols that are not exported and not used either.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The used pragma can be attached to a symbol to suppress this warning.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] used can also be used as a top-level statement to mark a module as "used".
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The experimental pragma enables experimental language features.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Depending on the concrete feature, this means that the feature is either considered too unstable for an otherwise stable release or that the future of the feature is uncertain (it may be removed at any time).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] See the experimental manual for more details.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] As a top-level statement, the experimental pragma enables a feature for the rest of the module it's enabled in.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] This is problematic for macro and generic instantiations that cross a module scope.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] This section describes additional pragmas that the current Nim implementation supports but which should not be seen as part of the language specification.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The bitsize pragma is for object field members.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] It declares the field as a bitfield in C/C++.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Nim automatically determines the size of an enum.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] But when wrapping a C enum type, it needs to be of a specific size.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The size pragma allows specifying the size of the enum type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] When used for enum types, the size pragma accepts only the values 1, 2, 4 or 8.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The size pragma can also specify the size of an importc incomplete object type so that one can get the size of it at compile time even if it was declared without fields.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The align pragma is for variables and object field members.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] It modifies the alignment requirement of the entity being declared.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The argument must be a constant power of 2.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Valid non-zero alignments that are weaker than other align pragmas on the same declaration are ignored.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Alignments that are weaker than the alignment requirement of the type are ignored.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] This pragma has no effect on the JavaScript backend and may significantly increase memory usage with the --mm:refc option.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Since version 1.4 of the Nim compiler, there is a .noalias annotation for variables and parameters.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] It is mapped directly to C/C++'s restrict keyword and means that the underlying pointer is pointing to a unique location in memory, no other aliases to this location exist.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] It is *unchecked* that this alias restriction is followed.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] If the restriction is violated, the backend optimizer is free to miscompile the code.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Ideally in later versions of the language, the restriction will be enforced at compile time.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The volatile pragma is for variables only.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] It declares the variable as volatile, whatever that means in C/C++ (its semantics are not well-defined in C/C++).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The nodecl pragma can be applied to almost any symbol (variable, proc, type, etc.) and is sometimes useful for interoperability with C: It tells Nim that it should not generate a declaration for the symbol in the C code.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] However, the header pragma is often the better alternative.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The header pragma always expects a string constant.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The string constant contains the header file: As usual for C, a system header file is enclosed in angle brackets: <>.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] If no angle brackets are given, Nim encloses the header file in "" in the generated C code.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The completeStruct pragma is a contract indicating that an importc type declaration contains all fields of the corresponding C type, allowing sizeof, alignof, and offsetof to be computed at compile-time.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] By default, importc types are assumed to be incomplete (their size is unknown at compile-time).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] If the Nim fields don't match the C struct, a static assertion will fail during C code generation.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Without completeStruct, attempting to use sizeof on an importc type at compile-time will error with "'sizeof' requires '.importc' types to be '.completeStruct'".
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] As can be seen in the example, this new variant allows for custom flags that are passed to the C compiler when the file is recompiled.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The emit pragma can be used to directly affect the output of the compiler's code generator.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The code is then unportable to other code generators/backends.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] However, it can be extremely useful for interfacing with C++ or Objective C code.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] statement is a single string literal, Nim symbols can be referred to via backticks.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] Similar to the importc pragma for C, the importcpp pragma can be used to import C++ methods or C++ symbols in general.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p04] The generated code then uses the C++ method calling syntax: obj->method(arg).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The compiler needs to be told to generate C++ (command cpp) for this to work.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The conditional symbol cpp is defined when the compiler emits C++ code.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The *sloppy interfacing* example uses .emit to produce using namespace declarations.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] When importcpp is applied to an enum type the numerical enum values are annotated with the C++ enum type, like in this example: ((TheCppEnum)(3)).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Sometimes a C++ class has a private copy constructor and so code like Class c = Class(1,2); must not be generated but instead Class c(1,2);.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] For this purpose the Nim proc that wraps a C++ constructor needs to be annotated with the constructor pragma.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Since Nim generates C++ directly, any destructor is called implicitly by the C++ compiler at the scope exits.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] This means that often one can get away with not wrapping the destructor at all!
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] However, when it needs to be invoked explicitly, it needs to be wrapped.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Generic importcpp'ed objects are mapped to C++ templates.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Similar to the importcpp pragma for C++, the importjs pragma can be used to import Javascript methods or symbols in general.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The generated code then uses the Javascript method calling syntax: obj.method(arg).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Similar to the importc pragma for C, the importobjc pragma can be used to import Objective C methods.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The generated code then uses the Objective C method calling syntax: [obj method param1: arg].
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The compiler needs to be told to generate Objective C (command objc) for this to work.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The conditional symbol objc is defined when the compiler emits Objective C code.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The codegenDecl pragma can be used to directly influence Nim's code generator.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] It receives a format string that determines how the variable, proc or object type is declared in the generated code.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] For variables, $1 in the format string represents the type of the variable, $2 is the name of the variable, and each appearance of $# represents $1/$2 respectively according to its position.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] For procedures, $1 is the return type of the procedure, $2 is the name of the procedure, $3 is the parameter list, and each appearance of $# represents $1/$2/$3 respectively according to its position.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] For object types, the $1 represents the name of the object type, $2 is the list of fields and $3 is the base type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The cppNonPod pragma should be used for non-POD importcpp types so that they work properly (in particular regarding constructor and destructor) for threadvar variables.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The pragmas listed here can be used to optionally accept values from the -d/--define option at compile time.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] In the above example, providing the -d flag causes the symbol FooBar to be overwritten at compile-time, printing out 42.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] If the -d:FooBar=42 were to be omitted, the default value of 5 would be used.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] To see if a value was provided, defined(FooBar) can be used.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The syntax -d:flag is actually just a shortcut for -d:flag=true.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] These pragmas also accept an optional string argument for qualified define names.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] This helps disambiguate define names in different packages.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] See also the generic `define` pragma for a version of these pragmas that detects the type of the define based on the constant value.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The pragma pragma can be used to declare user-defined pragmas.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] This is useful because Nim's templates and macros do not affect pragmas.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] User-defined pragmas are in a different module-wide scope than all other symbols.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] In the example, a new pragma named rtl is introduced that either imports a symbol from a dynamic library or exports the symbol for dynamic library generation.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] It is possible to define custom typed pragmas.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Custom pragmas do not affect code generation directly, but their presence can be detected by macros.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] In this example, custom pragmas are used to describe how Nim objects are mapped to the schema of the relational database.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Custom pragmas can have zero or more arguments.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] In order to pass multiple arguments use one of template call syntaxes.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] All arguments are typed and follow standard overload resolution rules for templates.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Therefore, it is possible to have default values for arguments, pass by name, varargs, etc.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Custom pragmas can be used in all locations where ordinary pragmas can be specified.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] It is possible to annotate procs, templates, type and variable definitions, statements, etc.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The macros module includes helpers which can be used to simplify custom pragma access hasCustomPragma, getCustomPragmaVal.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Please consult the macros module documentation for details.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] These macros are not magic, everything they do can also be achieved by walking the AST of the object representation.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Macros and templates can sometimes be called with the pragma syntax.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Cases where this is possible include when attached to routine (procs, iterators, etc.) declarations or routine type expressions.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] When multiple macro pragmas are applied to the same definition, the first one from left to right will be evaluated.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] This macro can then choose to keep the remaining macro pragmas in its output, and those will be evaluated in the same way.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] There are a few more applications of macro pragmas, such as in type, variable and constant declarations, but this behavior is considered to be experimental and is documented in the experimental manual instead.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Nim's FFI (foreign function interface) is extensive and only the parts that scale to other future backends (like the LLVM/JavaScript backends) are documented here.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The importc pragma provides a means to import a proc or a variable from C.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The optional argument is a string containing the C identifier.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] When importc is applied to a let statement it can omit its value which will then be expected to come from C.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Note that this pragma has been abused in the past to also work in the JS backend for JS objects and functions.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Other backends do provide the same feature under the same name.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] In the example, the external name of p is set to prefixp.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Only $1 is available and a literal dollar sign must be written as $$.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The exportc pragma provides a means to export a type, a variable, or a procedure to C.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Note that this pragma is somewhat of a misnomer: Other backends do provide the same feature under the same name.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] If the symbol should also be exported to a dynamic library, the dynlib pragma should be used in addition to the exportc pragma.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The exportcpp pragma works like the exportc pragma but it requires the cpp backend.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] When compiled with the cpp backend, the exportc pragma adds export "C" to the declaration in the generated code so that it can be called from both C and C++ code. exportcpp pragma doesn't add export "C".
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Like exportc or importc, the extern pragma affects name mangling.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The bycopy pragma can be applied to an object or tuple type or a proc param.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The Nim compiler automatically determines whether a parameter is passed by value or by reference based on the parameter type's size.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] If a parameter must be passed by value or by reference, (such as when interfacing with a C library) use the bycopy or byref pragmas.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Notice params marked as byref takes precedence over types marked as bycopy.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The byref pragma can be applied to an object or tuple type or a proc param.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] When applied to a type it instructs the compiler to pass the type by reference (hidden pointer) to procs.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] When applied to a param it will take precedence, even if the the type was marked as bycopy.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] When an importc type has a byref pragma or parameters are marked as byref in an importc proc, these params translate to pointers.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] When an importcpp type has a byref pragma, these params translate to C++ references &.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The varargs pragma can be applied to procedures only (and procedure types).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] It tells Nim that the proc can take a variable number of parameters after the last specified parameter.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The union pragma can be applied to any object type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] It means all of an object's fields are overlaid in memory.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] This produces a union instead of a struct in the generated C/C++ code.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The object declaration then must not use inheritance or any GC'ed memory but this is currently not checked.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The packed pragma can be applied to any object type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] It ensures that the fields of an object are packed back-to-back in memory.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] It is useful to store packets or messages from/to network or hardware drivers, and for interoperability with C.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Combining packed pragma with inheritance is not defined, and it should not be used with GC'ed memory (ref's).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] With the dynlib pragma, a procedure or a variable can be imported from a dynamic library (.dll files for Windows, lib*.so files for UNIX).
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] In general, importing a dynamic library does not require any special linker options or linking with import libraries.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] This also implies that no *devel* packages need to be installed.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] With the dynlib pragma, a procedure can also be exported to a dynamic library.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] This is only useful if the program is compiled as a dynamic library via the --app:lib command-line option.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The --threads:on command-line switch is enabled by default.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The typedthreads module module then contains several threading primitives.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The only ways to create a thread is via spawn or createThread.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] A proc that is executed as a new thread of execution should be marked by the thread pragma for reasons of readability.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The compiler checks for violations of the no heap sharing restriction: This restriction implies that it is invalid to construct a data structure that consists of memory allocated from different (thread-local) heaps.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] A thread proc can be passed to createThread or spawn.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] A variable can be marked with the threadvar pragma, which makes it a thread-local variable; Additionally, this implies all the effects of the global pragma.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Due to implementation restrictions, thread-local variables cannot be initialized within the var section.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The interaction between threads and exceptions is simple: A *handled* exception in one thread cannot affect any other thread.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] However, an *unhandled* exception in one thread terminates the whole *process*.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Nim provides common low level concurrency mechanisms like locks, atomic intrinsics or condition variables.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Every access of a guarded memory location needs to happen in an appropriate locks statement.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Top level accesses to gdata are always allowed so that it can be initialized conveniently.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] It is *assumed* (but not enforced) that every top level statement is executed before any concurrent action happens.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The locks section deliberately looks ugly because it has no runtime semantics and should not be used directly!
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The guard does not need to be of any particular type.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The locks pragma takes a list of lock expressions locks: [a, b, ...] in order to support *multi lock* statements.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The guard annotation can also be used to protect fields within an object.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The guard then needs to be another field within the same object or a global variable.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The access to field x.v is allowed since its guard x.L is active.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] There is an analysis that checks that counters[i].L is the lock that corresponds to the protected location counters[i].v.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] This analysis is called path analysis because it deals with paths to locations like obj.field[i].fieldB[j].
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] The path analysis is **currently unsound**, but that doesn't make it useless.
[src:nim-lang/manual-p05] Two paths are considered equivalent if they are syntactically the same.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming can be used to move computations from runtime to compile time, to generate code using compile time computations, and to enable self-modifying code.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] The ability of a programming language to be its own metalanguage allows reflective programming, and is termed *reflection*.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Reflection is a valuable language feature to facilitate metaprogramming.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming was popular in the 1970s and 1980s using list processing languages such as Lisp.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Lisp machine hardware gained some notice in the 1980s, and enabled applications that could process code.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] They were often used for artificial intelligence applications.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming enables developers to write programs and develop code that falls under the generic programming paradigm.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Having the programming language itself as a first-class data type (as in Lisp, Prolog, SNOBOL, or Rebol) is also very useful; this is known as *homoiconicity*.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Generic programming invokes a metaprogramming facility within a language by allowing one to write code without the concern of specifying data types since they can be supplied as parameters when used.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming usually works in one of three ways.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] The second approach is dynamic execution of expressions that contain programming commands, often composed from strings, but can also be from other methods using arguments or context, like JavaScript.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Thus, "programs can write programs." Although both approaches can be used in the same language, most languages tend to lean toward one or the other.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] The third approach is to step outside the language entirely.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] General purpose program transformation systems such as compilers, which accept language descriptions and carry out arbitrary transformations on those languages, are direct implementations of general metaprogramming.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] This allows metaprogramming to be applied to virtually any target language without regard to whether that target language has any metaprogramming abilities of its own.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] One can see this at work with Scheme and how it allows tackling some limits faced in C by using constructs that are part of the Scheme language to extend C.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Lisp is probably the quintessential language with metaprogramming facilities, both because of its historical precedence and because of the simplicity and power of its metaprogramming.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] In Lisp metaprogramming, the unquote operator (typically a comma) introduces code that is evaluated at program definition time rather than at run time.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] The metaprogramming language is thus identical to the host programming language, and existing Lisp routines can be directly reused for metaprogramming if desired.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] This approach has been implemented in other languages by incorporating an interpreter in the program, which works directly with the program's data.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] There are implementations of this kind for some common high-level languages, such as RemObjects’ Pascal Script for Object Pascal.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] This script (or program) generates a new 993-line program that prints out the numbers 1–992.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] This is only an illustration of how to use code to write more code; it is not the most efficient way to print out a list of numbers.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Nonetheless, a programmer can write and execute this metaprogram in less than a minute, and will have generated over 1000 lines of code in that amount of time.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] A quine is a special kind of metaprogram that produces its own source code as its output.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Quines are generally of recreational or theoretical interest only.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Not all metaprogramming involves generative programming.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] One style of generative approach is to employ domain-specific languages (DSLs).
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] One usage of metaprogramming is to instrument programs in order to do dynamic program analysis.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Some argue that there is a sharp learning curve to make complete use of metaprogramming features.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Since metaprogramming gives more flexibility and configurability at runtime, misuse or incorrect use of metaprogramming can result in unwarranted and unexpected errors that can be extremely difficult to debug to an average developer.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] It can introduce risks in the system and make it more vulnerable if not used with care.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Some of the common problems, which can occur due to wrong use of metaprogramming are inability of the compiler to identify missing configuration parameters, invalid or incorrect data can result in unknown exception or different results.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Due to this, some believe that only high-skilled developers should work on developing features which exercise metaprogramming in a language or platform and average developers must learn how to use these features as part of convention.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] The IBM/360 and derivatives had powerful macro assembler facilities that were often used to generate complete assembly language programs or sections of programs (for different operating systems for instance).
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Macros provided with CICS transaction processing system had assembler macros that generated COBOL statements as a pre-processing step.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Other assemblers, such as MASM, also support macros.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] Use of dependent types allows proving that generated code is never invalid.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] However, this approach is leading-edge and rarely found outside of research programming languages.
[src:nim-lang/metaprogramming] The list of notable metaprogramming systems is maintained at List of program transformation systems.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] It supports compile-time metaprogramming features such as syntactic macros and term rewriting macros.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Term rewriting macros enable library implementations of common data structures, such as bignums and matrices, to be implemented efficiently and with syntactic integration, as if they were built-in language facilities.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Iterators are supported and can be used as first class entities, as can functions, allowing for the use of functional programming methods.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Object-oriented programming is supported by inheritance and multiple dispatch.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Functions can be generic and overloaded, and generics are further enhanced by Nim's support for type classes.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim includes multiple tunable memory management strategies, including tracing garbage collection, reference counting, and fully manual systems, with the default being deterministic reference counting with optimizations via move semantics and cycle collection via trial deletion.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] — Andrew Binstock, editor-in-chief of Dr.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] As of August 2023, Nim compiles to C, C++, JavaScript, Objective-C, and LLVM.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Andreas Rumpf is the designer and original implementer of Nim.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] He received a diploma in computer science from the Technical University of Kaiserslautern, Germany.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] His research interests include hard real-time systems, embedded systems, compiler construction and artificial intelligence.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim's initial development was started in 2005 under the name *Nimrod* and was made public in 2008.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The first version of the Nim compiler was written in Pascal using the Free Pascal compiler.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] In 2008, a version of the compiler written in Nim was released.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The compiler is free and open-source software, and is being developed by a community of volunteers working with Andreas Rumpf.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The language was officially renamed from *Nimrod* to *Nim* with the release of version 0.10.2 in December 2014.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] On 23 September 2019, version 1.0 of Nim was released, signifying the maturing of the language and its toolchain.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] On 1 August 2023, version 2.0 of Nim was released, signifying the completion, stabilization of, and switch to the ARC/ORC memory model.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The syntax of Nim resembles that of Python.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Code blocks and nesting statements are identified through use of whitespace, according to the offside-rule.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Many keywords are identical to their Python equivalents, which are mostly English keywords, whereas other programming languages usually use punctuation.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] With the goal of improving upon its influence languages, even though Nim supports indentation-based syntax like Python, it introduced additional flexibility.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] For example, a single statement may span multiple lines if a comma or binary operator is at the end of each line.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim also supports user-defined operators.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Unlike Python, Nim implements (native) static typing.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim's type system allows for easy type conversion, casting, and provides syntax for generic programming.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim notably provides type classes which can stand in for multiple types, and provides several such type classes 'out of the box'.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Type classes allow working with several types as if they were a single type.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] According to the language creator, Nim was conceived to combine the best parts of Ada typing system, Python flexibility, and powerful Lisp macro system.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim supports uniform function call syntax (UFCS) and identifier equality, which provides a large degree of flexibility in use.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim is almost fully style-insensitive; two identifiers are considered equal if they only differ by capitalization and underscores, as long as the first characters are identical.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] This is to enable a mixture of styles across libraries: one user can write a library using snake_case as a convention, and it can be used by a different user in a camelCase style without issue.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The stropping feature allows the use of any name for variables or functions, even when the names are reserved words for keywords.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] An example of stropping is the ability to define a variable named `if`, without clashing with the keyword `if`.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim's implementation of this is achieved via backticks, allowing any reserved word to be used as an identifier.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The Nim compiler emits fast, optimized C code by default.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] It defers compiling-to-object code to an external C compiler to leverage existing compiler optimization and portability.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Many C compilers are supported, including Clang, Microsoft Visual C++ (MSVC), MinGW, and GNU Compiler Collection (GCC).
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The Nim compiler can also emit C++, Objective-C, and JavaScript code to allow easy interfacing with application programming interfaces (APIs) written in those languages; developers can simply write in Nim, then compile to any supported language.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] This also allows writing applications for iOS and Android.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] There is also an unofficial LLVM backend, allowing use of the Nim compiler in a stand-alone way.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The Nim compiler is self-hosting, meaning it is written in the Nim language.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The compiler supports cross-compiling, so it is able to compile software for any of the supported operating systems, no matter the development machine.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] This is useful for compiling applications for embedded systems, and for uncommon and obscure computer architectures.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] By default, the Nim compiler creates a *debug* build.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] With the option `-d:release` a *release* build can be created, which is optimized for speed and contains fewer runtime checks.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] With the option `-d:danger` all runtime checks can be disabled, if maximum speed is desired.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nimble is the standard package manager used by Nim to package Nim modules.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] It was initially developed by Dominik Picheta, who is also a core Nim developer.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nimble has been included as Nim's official package manager since 27 October 2015, the v0.12.0 release.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nimble packages are defined by `.nimble` files, which contain information about the package version, author, license, description, dependencies, and more.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] These files support a limited subset of the Nim syntax called NimScript, with the main limitation being the access to the FFI.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] These scripts allow changing of test procedure, or for custom tasks to be written.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The list of packages is stored in a JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) file which is freely accessible in the nim-lang/packages repository on GitHub.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] This JSON file provides Nimble with a mapping between the names of packages and their Git or Mercurial repository URLs.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Thus, it is possible to test the Nimble environment by running: `nimble -v`.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] This command will reveal the version number, compiling date and time, and Git hash of nimble.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nimble uses the Git package, which must be available for Nimble to function properly.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The Nimble command-line is used as an interface for installing, removing (uninstalling), and upgrading–patching module packages.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] c2nim is a source-to-source compiler (transcompiler or transpiler) meant to be used on C/C++ headers to help generate new Nim bindings.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The output is human-readable Nim code that is meant to be edited by hand after the translation process.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] koch is a maintenance script that is used to build Nim, and provide HTML documentation.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] nimgrep is a generic tool for manipulating text.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] It is used to search for regex, peg patterns, and contents of directories, and it can be used to replace tasks.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] It is included to assist with searching Nim's style-insensitive identifiers.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] nimsuggest is a tool that helps any source code editor query a `.nim` source file to obtain useful information like definition of symbols or suggestions for completions.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] niminst is a tool to generate an installer for a Nim program.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] It creates .msi installers for Windows via Inno Setup, and install and uninstall scripts for Linux, macOS, and Berkeley Software Distribution (BSD).
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] nimpretty is a source code beautifier, used to format code according to the official Nim style guide.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Testament is an advanced automatic unit tests runner for Nim tests.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Used in developing Nim, it offers process isolation tests, generates statistics about test cases, supports multiple targets and simulated Dry-Runs, has logging, can generate HTML reports, can skip tests from a file, and more.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] choosenim was developed by Dominik Picheta, creator of the Nimble package manager, as a tool to enable installing and using multiple versions of the Nim compiler.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] It downloads any Nim stable or development compiler version from the command line, enabling easy switching between them.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] nimpy is a library that enables convenient Python integration in Nim programs.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] pixie is a feature-rich 2D graphics library, similar to Cairo or the Skia.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] It uses SIMD acceleration to speed-up image manipulation drastically.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] It supports many image formats, blending, masking, blurring, and can be combined with the boxy library to do hardware accelerated rendering.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] nimterop is a tool focused on automating the creation of C/C++ wrappers needed for Nim's foreign function interface.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Pure libraries are modules written in Nim only.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] They include no wrappers to access libraries written in other programming languages.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Impure libraries are modules of Nim code which depend on external libraries that are written in other programming languages such as C.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] A Nim program can use any library which can be used in a C, C++, or JavaScript program.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Language bindings exist for many libraries, including GTK, Qt QML, wxWidgets, SDL 2, Raylib, Godot, UE5, Cairo, OpenGL, Vulkan, Windows API (WinAPI), zlib, libzip, OpenSSL and cURL.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim works with databases PostgreSQL, MySQL, and SQLite.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Open source tools exist, of various degrees of support, that can be used to interface Nim with the languages Lua, Julia, Rust, C#, and Python, or transpile Nim to TypeScript.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] A simple demonstration showing the implicit result variable and the use of iterators.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] One of Nim's more exotic features is the implicit `result` variable.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Every procedure in Nim with a non-void return type has an implicit result variable that represents the value to be returned.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] In the for loop we see an invocation of `countdown` which is an iterator.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] If an iterator is omitted, the compiler will attempt to use an `items` iterator, if one is defined for the type specified.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] This code requires the gintro module to work, which is not part of the standard library.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] To install the module gintro and many others you can use the tool nimble, which comes as part of Nim.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Functional programming is supported in Nim through first-class functions and code without side effects via the `noSideEffect` pragma or the `func` keyword.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim will perform side effect analysis and raise compiling errors for code that does not obey the contract of producing no side effects when compiled with the experimental feature `strictFuncs`, planned to become the default in later versions.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Contrary to purely functional programming languages, Nim is a multi-paradigm programming language, so functional programming restrictions are opt-in on a function-by-function basis.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim supports first-class functions by allowing functions to be stored in variables or passed anonymously as parameters to be invoked by other functions.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The `std/sugar` module provides syntactic sugar for anonymous functions in type declarations and instantiation.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Side effects of functions annotated with the `noSideEffect` pragma are checked, and the compiler will refuse to compile functions failing to meet those.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Side effects in Nim include mutation, global state access or modification, asynchronous code, threaded code, and IO.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Mutation of parameters may occur for functions taking parameters of `var` or `ref` type: this is expected to fail to compile with the currently-experimental `strictFuncs` in the future.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The `func` keyword introduces a shortcut for a `noSideEffect` pragma.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Uniform function call syntax allows the chaining of arbitrary functions, perhaps best exemplified with the `std/sequtils` library.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim has support for product types via the `object` type, and for sum types via object variants: raw representations of tagged unions, with an enumerated type tag that must be safely matched upon before fields of variants can be accessed.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] These types can be composed algebraically.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Structural pattern matching is available, but relegated to macros in various third-party libraries.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Despite being primarily an imperative and functional language, Nim supports various features for enabling object-oriented paradigms.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim supports limited inheritance by use of `ref objects` and the `of` keyword.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] To enable inheritance, any initial ("root") object must inherit from `RootObj`.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Inheritance is of limited use within idiomatic Nim code: with the notable exception of Exceptions.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Subtyping relations can also be queried with the `of` keyword.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim's uniform function call syntax enables calling ordinary functions with syntax similar to method call invocations in other programming languages.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] This is functional for "getters": and Nim also provides syntax for the creation of such "setters" as well.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Objects may be made public on a per-field basis, providing for encapsulation.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Static dispatch is preferred, more performant, and standard even among method-looking routines.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nonetheless, if dynamic dispatch is so desired, Nim provides the `method` keyword for enabling dynamic dispatch on reference types.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim supports simple substitution on the abstract syntax tree via its templates.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The `genType` is invoked at compile-time and a `Test` type is created.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim supports both constrained and unconstrained generic programming.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Generics may be used in procedures, templates and macros.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Unconstrained generic identifiers (`T` in this example) are defined after the routine's name in square brackets.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Constrained generics can be placed on generic identifiers, or directly on parameters.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] One can further clarify which types the procedure will accept by specifying a type class (in the example above, `SomeSignedInt`).
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Macros can rewrite parts of the code at compile-time.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim macros are powerful and can operate on the abstract syntax tree before or after semantic checking.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The `twice` macro in this example takes the echo statement in the form of an abstract syntax tree as input.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] In this example we decided to return this syntax tree without any manipulations applied to it.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] But we do it twice, hence the name of the macro.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim's FFI is used to call functions written in the other programming languages that it can compile to.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] This means that libraries written in C, C++, Objective-C, and JavaScript can be used in the Nim source code.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] One should be aware that both JavaScript and C, C++, or Objective-C libraries cannot be combined in the same program, as they are not as compatible with JavaScript as they are with each other.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Both C++ and Objective-C are based on and compatible with C, but JavaScript is incompatible, as a dynamic, client-side web-based language.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The following program shows the ease with which external C code can be used directly in Nim.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] In this code the `printf` function is imported into Nim and then used.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The JavaScript code produced by the Nim compiler can be executed with Node.js or a web browser.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] To activate threading support in Nim, a program should be compiled with `--threads:on` command line argument.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Each thread has a separate garbage collected heap and sharing of memory is restricted, which helps with efficiency and stops race conditions by the threads.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim also has a `channels` module that simplifies passing data between threads.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Asynchronous IO is supported either via the `asyncdispatch` module in the standard library or the external `chronos` library.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Both libraries add async/await syntax via the macro system, without need for special language support.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Nim has an active community on the self-hosted, self-developed official forum.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Further, the project uses a Git repository, bug tracker, RFC tracker, and wiki hosted by GitHub, where the community engages with the language.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] There are also official online chat rooms, bridged between IRC, Matrix, Discord, Gitter, and Telegram.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The first Nim conference, NimConf, took place on 20 June 2020.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] It was held digitally due to COVID-19, with an open call for contributor talks in the form of YouTube videos.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] The conference began with language overviews by Nim developers Andreas Rumpf and Dominik Picheta.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Presentation topics included talks about web frameworks, mobile development, Internet of things (IoT) devices, and game development, including a talk about writing Nim for Game Boy Advance.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] NimConf 2020 is available as a YouTube playlist.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] NimConf 2021 occurred the following year, was also held digitally, and included talks about game development, REPLs, real-time operating systems, Nim in the industry, object–relational mapping (ORM), fuzzing, language design, and graphics libraries.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] In addition to official conferences, Nim has been featured at various other conventions.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] A presentation on Nim was given at the O'Reilly Open Source Convention (OSCON) in 2015.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Four speakers represented Nim at FOSDEM 2020, including the creator of the language, Andreas Rumpf.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] At FOSDEM 2022, Nim hosted their own developer room virtually due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:nim-lang/nim-programming-language] Talks were held on concurrency, embedded programming, programming for GPUs, entity-component systems, game development, rules engines, Python interop, and metaprogramming.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] Systems programming requires a great degree of hardware awareness.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] Its goal is to achieve efficient use of available resources, either because the software itself is performance-critical or because even small efficiency improvements directly transform into significant savings of time or money.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] In systems programming, often limited programming facilities are available.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] The use of automatic garbage collection is not common and debugging is sometimes hard to do.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] The runtime library, if available at all, is usually far less powerful, and does less error checking.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] Because of those limitations, monitoring and logging are often used; operating systems may have extremely elaborate logging subsystems.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] Implementing certain parts in operating systems and networking requires systems programming, for example implementing paging (virtual memory) or a device driver for an operating system.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] Originally systems programmers invariably wrote in assembly language.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] Experiments with hardware support in high level languages in the late 1960s led to such languages as PL/S, BLISS, BCPL, and extended ALGOL for Burroughs Large Systems.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] Forth also has applications as a systems language.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] In the 1970s, C became widespread, aided by the growth of Unix.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] More recently a subset of C++ called Embedded C++ has seen some use, for instance it is used in the I/O Kit drivers of macOS.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] Engineers working at Google created Go in 2007 to address developer productivity in large distributed systems, with developer-focused features such as Concurrency, Garbage Collection, and faster program compilation than C and C++.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] In 2015 Rust came out, a general-purpose programming language often used in systems programming.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] Rust was designed with memory safety in mind and to be as performant as C and C++.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] For historical reasons, some organizations use the term *systems programmer* to describe a job function which would be more accurately termed systems administrator.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] This is particularly true in organizations whose computer resources have historically been dominated by mainframes, although the term is even used to describe job functions which do not involve mainframes.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] This usage arose because administration of IBM mainframes often involved the writing of custom assembler code (IBM's Basic Assembly Language (BAL)), which integrated with the operating system such as OS/MVS, DOS/VSE or VM/CMS.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] Indeed, some IBM software products had substantial code contributions from customer programming staff.
[src:nim-lang/systems-programming] This type of programming is progressively less common, and increasingly done in C rather than Assembly, but the term *systems programmer* is still used as the de-facto job title for staff administering IBM mainframes even in cases where they do not regularly engage in systems programming activities.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This document is a tutorial for the programming language *Nim*.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This tutorial assumes that you are familiar with basic programming concepts like variables, types, or statements.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] All code examples in this tutorial, as well as the ones found in the rest of Nim's documentation, follow the Nim style guide.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Save this code to the file "greetings.nim".
[src:nim-lang/tut1] With the --run switch Nim executes the file automatically after compilation.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] By default, the Nim compiler generates a large number of runtime checks aiming for your debugging pleasure.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] With -d:release some checks are turned off and optimizations are turned on.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] For benchmarking or production code, use the -d:release switch.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] For comparing the performance with unsafe languages like C, use the -d:danger switch in order to get meaningful, comparable results.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Otherwise, Nim might be handicapped by checks that are **not even available** for C.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Though it should be pretty obvious what the program does, I will explain the syntax: statements which are not indented are executed when the program starts.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Indentation is Nim's way of grouping statements.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Indentation is done with spaces only, tabulators are not allowed.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] String literals are enclosed in double-quotes.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The var statement declares a new variable named name of type string with the value that is returned by the readLine procedure.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Since the compiler knows that readLine returns a string, you can leave out the type in the declaration (this is called local type inference).
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Note that this is basically the only form of type inference that exists in Nim: it is a good compromise between brevity and readability.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The "hello world" program contains several identifiers that are already known to the compiler: echo, readLine, etc.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] These built-ins are declared in the system module which is implicitly imported by any other module.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Let us look at Nim's lexical elements in more detail: like other programming languages Nim consists of (string) literals, identifiers, keywords, comments, operators, and other punctuation marks.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] String literals are enclosed in double-quotes; character literals in single quotes.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Special characters are escaped with \: \n means newline, \t means tabulator, etc.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] In raw literals, the backslash is not an escape character.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The third and last way to write string literals is *long-string literals*.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] They are written with three quotes: """ ...
[src:nim-lang/tut1] """; they can span over multiple lines and the \ is not an escape character either.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] They are very useful for embedding HTML code templates for example.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Documentation comments are tokens; they are only allowed at certain places in the input file as they belong to the syntax tree!
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This feature enables simpler documentation generators.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Multiline comments are started with #[ and terminated with ].
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Numerical literals are written as in most other languages.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] As a special twist, underscores are allowed for better readability: 1_000_000 (one million).
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A number that contains a dot (or 'e' or 'E') is a floating-point literal: 1.0e9 (one billion).
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Hexadecimal literals are prefixed with 0x, binary literals with 0b and octal literals with 0o.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A leading zero alone does not produce an octal.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Constants are symbols which are bound to a value.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The assignment operator can be overloaded.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The greetings program consists of 3 statements that are executed sequentially.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Only the most primitive programs can get away with that: branching and looping are needed too.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] There can be zero or more elif parts, and the else part is optional.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The keyword elif is short for else if, and is useful to avoid excessive indentation.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Another way to branch is provided by the case statement.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] As it can be seen, for an of branch a comma-separated list of values is also allowed.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The case statement can deal with integers, other ordinal types, and strings.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] However, the above code **does not compile**: the reason is that you have to cover every value that n may contain, but the code only handles the values 0..8.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The empty discard statement is a *do nothing* statement.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The compiler knows that a case statement with an else part cannot fail and thus the error disappears.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Note that it is impossible to cover all possible string values: that is why string cases always need an else branch.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] In general, the case statement is used for subrange types or enumerations where it is of great help that the compiler checks that you covered any possible value.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The example uses a while loop to keep asking the users for their name, as long as the user types in nothing (only presses RETURN).
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The for statement is a construct to loop over any element an *iterator* provides.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The variable i is implicitly declared by the for loop and has the type int, because that is what countup returns. i runs through the values 1, 2, .., 10.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] var s = "some string" for i in 0 ..< s.len: ...
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Control flow statements have a feature not covered yet: they open a new scope.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A while (for) statement introduces an implicit block.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Identifiers are only visible within the block they have been declared.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The block's *label* (myblock in the example) is optional.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A block can be left prematurely with a break statement.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The break statement can leave a while, for, or a block statement.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The when statement is useful for writing platform-specific code, similar to the #ifdef construct in the C programming language.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Now that we covered the basic control flow statements, let's return to Nim indentation rules.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] In Nim, there is a distinction between *simple statements* and *complex statements*.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] *Simple statements* cannot contain other statements: Assignment, procedure calls, or the return statement are all simple statements.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] *Complex statements* like if, when, for, while can contain other statements.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] As a rule of thumb, indentation within expressions is allowed after operators, an open parenthesis and after commas.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] To define new commands like echo and readLine in the examples, the concept of a *procedure* is needed.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] You might be used to them being called *methods* or *functions* in other languages, but Nim differentiates these concepts.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This example shows a procedure named yes that asks the user a question and returns true if they answered "yes" (or something similar) and returns false if they answered "no" (or something similar).
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A return statement leaves the procedure (and therefore the while loop) immediately.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The (question: string): bool syntax describes that the procedure expects a parameter named question of type string and returns a value of type bool.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The bool type is built-in: the only valid values for bool are true and false.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The conditions in if or while statements must be of type bool.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Some terminology: in the example question is called a (formal) *parameter*, "Should I..." is called an *argument* that is passed to this parameter.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A procedure that returns a value has an implicit result variable declared that represents the return value.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A return statement with no expression is shorthand for return result.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The result value is always returned automatically at the end of a procedure if there is no return statement at the exit.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The result variable is already implicitly declared at the start of the function, so declaring it again with 'var result', for example, would shadow it with a normal variable of the same name.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The result variable is also already initialized with the type's default value.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Note that referential data types will be nil at the start of the procedure, and thus may require manual initialization.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A procedure that does not have any return statement and does not use the special result variable returns the value of its last expression.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Parameters are immutable in the procedure body.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] By default, their value cannot be changed because this allows the compiler to implement parameter passing in the most efficient way.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] If a mutable variable is needed inside the procedure, it has to be declared with var in the procedure body.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Note that the above example would better make use of a tuple as a return value instead of using var parameters.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] To call a procedure that returns a value just for its side effects and ignoring its return value, a discard statement **must** be used.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Often a procedure has many parameters and it is not clear in which order the parameters appear.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This is especially true for procedures that construct a complex data type.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Now that we use named arguments to call createWindow the argument order does not matter anymore.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The compiler checks that each parameter receives exactly one argument.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Now the call to createWindow only needs to set the values that differ from the defaults.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Note that type inference works for parameters with default values; there is no need to write title: string = "unknown", for example.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] (Note that toString is usually the $ operator in Nim.) The compiler chooses the most appropriate proc for the toString calls.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] How this overloading resolution algorithm works exactly is not discussed here -- see the manual for details.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The Nim standard library makes heavy use of overloading - one reason for this is that each operator like + is just an overloaded proc.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The parser lets you use operators in *infix notation* (a + b) or *prefix notation* (+ a).
[src:nim-lang/tut1] An infix operator always receives two arguments, a prefix operator always one.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] (Postfix operators are not possible, because this would be ambiguous: does a @ @ b mean (a) @ (@b) or (a@) @ (b)?
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Nothing stops you from defining your own @!?+~ operator, but doing so may reduce readability.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The operator's precedence is determined by its first character.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Every variable, procedure, etc. needs to be declared before it can be used.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Here odd depends on even and vice versa.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Thus even needs to be introduced to the compiler before it is completely defined.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The syntax for such a forward declaration is simple: just omit the = and the procedure's body.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The assert just adds border conditions, and will be covered later in Modules section.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Later versions of the language will weaken the requirements for forward declarations.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The example also shows that a proc's body can consist of a single expression whose value is then returned implicitly.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] As mentioned in the introduction, Nim differentiates between procedures, functions, and methods, defined by the proc, func, and method keywords respectively.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] In some ways, Nim is a bit more pedantic in its definitions than other languages.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Functions are closer to the concept of a pure mathematical function, which might be familiar to you if you've ever done functional programming.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Essentially they are procedures with additional limitations set on them: they can't access global state (except const) and can't produce side-effects.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The func keyword is basically an alias for proc tagged with {.noSideEffects.}.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Functions can still change their mutable arguments however, which are those marked as var, along with any ref objects.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Unlike procedures, methods are dynamically dispatched.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This sounds a bit complicated, but it is a concept closely related to inheritance and object-oriented programming.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] If you overload a procedure (two procedures with the same name but of different types or with different sets of arguments are said to be overloaded), the procedure to use is determined at compile-time.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Methods, on the other hand, depend on objects that inherit from the RootObj.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This is something that is covered in much greater depth in the second part of the tutorial.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Can a countup proc be written that supports this loop?
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The problem is that the procedure should not only return, but return and **continue** after an iteration has finished.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This *return and continue* is called a yield statement.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] However, you can also use a closure iterator to get a different set of restrictions.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Iterators can have the same name and parameters as a proc since essentially they have their own namespaces.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Therefore, it is common to wrap iterators in procs of the same name which accumulate the result of the iterator and return it as a sequence, like split from the strutils module.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This section deals with the basic built-in types and the operations that are available for them in detail.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Nim's boolean type is called bool and consists of the two pre-defined values true and false.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Conditions in while, if, elif, and when statements must be of type bool.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The operators not, and, or, xor, <, <=, >, >=, !=, == are defined for the bool type.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The and and or operators perform short-circuit evaluation.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Its size is always one byte, so it cannot represent most UTF-8 characters, but it *can* represent one of the bytes that makes up a multibyte UTF-8 character.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The reason for this is efficiency: for the overwhelming majority of use-cases, the resulting programs will still handle UTF-8 properly as UTF-8 was especially designed for this.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Character literals are enclosed in single quotes.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Chars can be compared with the ==, <, <=, >, >= operators.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The $ operator converts a char to a string.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Chars cannot be mixed with integers; to get the ordinal value of a char use the ord proc.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Converting from an integer to a char is done with the chr proc.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] String variables are **mutable**, so appending to a string is possible, and quite efficient.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Strings in Nim are both zero-terminated and have a length field.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A string's length can be retrieved with the builtin len procedure; the length never counts the terminating zero.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Accessing the terminating zero is an error, it only exists so that a Nim string can be converted to a cstring without doing a copy.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The assignment operator for strings copies the string.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] You can use the & operator to concatenate strings and add to append to a string.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Strings are compared using their lexicographical order.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] All the comparison operators are supported.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] By convention, all strings are UTF-8 encoded, but this is not enforced.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] For example, when reading strings from binary files, they are merely a sequence of bytes.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The index operation s[i] means the i-th *char* of s, not the i-th *unichar*.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A string variable is initialized with the empty string "".
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Nim has these integer types built-in: int int8 int16 int32 int64 uint uint8 uint16 uint32 uint64.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Most often integers are used for counting objects that reside in memory, so int has the same size as a pointer.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The common operators + - * div mod < <= == != > >= are defined for integers.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The and or xor not operators are also defined for integers and provide *bitwise* operations.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Left bit shifting is done with the shl, right shifting with the shr operator.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Bit shifting operators always treat their arguments as *unsigned*.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] For arithmetic bit shifts ordinary multiplication or division can be used.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Unsigned operations all wrap around; they cannot lead to over- or under-flow errors.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Lossless Automatic type conversion is performed in expressions where different kinds of integer types are used.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] However, if the type conversion would cause loss of information, the RangeDefect is raised (if the error cannot be detected at compile time).
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Nim has these floating-point types built-in: float float32 float64.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] In the current implementation, float is always 64-bits.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The common operators + - * / < <= == != > >= are defined for floats and follow the IEEE-754 standard.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Automatic type conversion in expressions with different kinds of floating-point types is performed: the smaller type is converted to the larger.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Integer types are **not** converted to floating-point types automatically, nor vice versa.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Use the toInt and toFloat procs for these conversions.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] As mentioned earlier, the built-in $ (stringify) operator turns any basic type into a string, which you can then print to the console using the echo proc.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] However, advanced types, and your own custom types, won't work with the $ operator until you define it for them.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Sometimes you just want to debug the current value of a complex type without having to write its $ operator.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] You can use then the repr proc which works with any type and even complex data graphs with cycles.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Enumeration and object types may only be defined within a type statement.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A variable of an enumeration type can only be assigned one of the enumeration's specified values.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] These values are a set of ordered symbols.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Each symbol is mapped to an integer value internally.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The first symbol is represented at runtime by 0, the second by 1, and so on.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] All the comparison operators can be used with enumeration types.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] An enumeration's symbol can be qualified to avoid ambiguities: Direction.south.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The $ operator can convert any enumeration value to its name, and the ord proc can convert it to its underlying integer value.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] For better interfacing to other programming languages, the symbols of enum types can be assigned an explicit ordinal value.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] However, the ordinal values must be in ascending order.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Enumerations, integer types, char and bool (and subranges) are called ordinal types.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The inc, dec, succ and pred operations can fail by raising an RangeDefect or OverflowDefect.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A subrange type is a range of values from an integer or enumeration type (the base type).
[src:nim-lang/tut1] MySubrange is a subrange of int which can only hold the values 0 to 5.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Assigning any other value to a variable of type MySubrange is a compile-time or runtime error.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Assignments from the base type to one of its subrange types (and vice versa) are allowed.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The system module defines the important Natural type as range[0..high(int)] (high returns the maximal value).
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Other programming languages may suggest the use of unsigned integers for natural numbers.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This is often **unwise**: you don't want unsigned arithmetic (which wraps around) just because the numbers cannot be negative.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Nim's Natural type helps to avoid this common programming error.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The set type models the mathematical notion of a set.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] When constructing a set with signed integer literals, the set's base type is defined to be in the range 0 ..
[src:nim-lang/tut1] DefaultSetElements-1 where DefaultSetElements is currently always 2^8.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The maximum range length for the base type of a set is MaxSetElements which is currently always 2^16.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Types with a bigger range length are coerced into the range 0 ..
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The reason is that sets are implemented as high performance bit vectors.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Sets can be constructed via the set constructor: {} is the empty set.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The empty set is type compatible with any concrete set type.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Sets are often used to define a type for the *flags* of a procedure.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This is a cleaner (and type safe) solution than defining integer constants that have to be or'ed together.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Note how the set turns enum values into powers of 2.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] If using enums and sets with C, use distinct cint.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] For interoperability with C see also the bitsize pragma.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] An array is a simple fixed-length container.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Each element in an array has the same type.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The array's index type can be any ordinal type.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The notation x[i] is used to access the i-th element of x in the example above.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Valid indexes can be defined by any subrange.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Array access is always bounds checked (at compile-time or at runtime).
[src:nim-lang/tut1] These checks can be disabled via pragmas or invoking the compiler with the --bound_checks:off command line switch.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Arrays are value types, like any other Nim type.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The assignment operator copies the whole array contents.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The built-in len proc returns the array's length. low(a) returns the lowest valid index for the array a and high(a) the highest valid index.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The syntax for nested arrays (multidimensional) in other languages is a matter of appending more brackets because usually each dimension is restricted to the same index type as the others.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] In Nim you can have different dimensions with different index types, so the nesting syntax is slightly different.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Note how the built-in len proc returns only the array's first dimension length.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Sequences are similar to arrays but of dynamic length which may change during runtime (like strings).
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Since sequences are resizable they are always allocated on the heap and garbage collected.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Sequences are always indexed with an int starting at position 0.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The len, low and high operations are available for sequences too.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The notation x[i] can be used to access the i-th element of x.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Sequences can be constructed by the array constructor [] in conjunction with the array to sequence operator @.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Another way to allocate space for a sequence is to call the built-in newSeq procedure.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A sequence may be passed to an openarray parameter.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Sequence variables are initialized with @[].
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The for statement can be used with one or two variables when used with a sequence.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] When you use the one variable form, the variable will hold the value provided by the sequence.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The for statement is looping over the results from the items() iterator from the system module.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] But if you use the two-variable form, the first variable will hold the index position and the second variable will hold the value.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Here the for statement is looping over the results from the pairs() iterator from the system module.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Often fixed-size arrays turn out to be too inflexible; procedures should be able to deal with arrays of different sizes.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Openarrays are always indexed with an int starting at position 0.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The len, low and high operations are available for open arrays too.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Any array with a compatible base type can be passed to an openarray parameter, the index type does not matter.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The openarray type cannot be nested: multidimensional openarrays are not supported because this is seldom needed and cannot be done efficiently.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A varargs parameter is like an openarray parameter.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] However, it is also a means to implement passing a variable number of arguments to a procedure.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This transformation is only done if the varargs parameter is the last parameter in the procedure header.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] In this example $ is applied to any argument that is passed to the parameter a.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Note that $ applied to strings is a nop.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Slices look similar to subranges types in syntax but are used in a different context.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A slice is just an object of type Slice which contains two bounds, a and b.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] By itself a slice is not very useful, but other collection types define operators which accept Slice objects to define ranges.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] var a = "Nim is a programming language" b = "Slices are useless." echo a[7 ..
[src:nim-lang/tut1] In the previous example slices are used to modify a part of a string.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The slice's bounds can hold any value supported by their type, but it is the proc using the slice object which defines what values are accepted.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] To understand the different ways of specifying the indices of strings, arrays, sequences, etc., it must be remembered that Nim uses zero-based indices.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] where b[0 .. ^1] is equivalent to b[0 .. b.len-1] and b[0 ..< b.len], and it can be seen that the ^1 provides a shorthand way of specifying the b.len-1.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] In the above example, because the string ends in a period, to get the portion of the string that is "useless" and replace it with "useful".
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Note 2: As the ^ template returns a distinct int of type BackwardsIndex, we can have a lastIndex constant defined as const lastIndex = ^1, and later used as b[0 .. lastIndex].
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The default type to pack different values together in a single structure with a name is the object type.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] An object is a value type, which means that when an object is assigned to a new variable all its components are copied as well.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Each object type Foo has a constructor Foo(field: value, ...) where all of its fields can be initialized.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Unspecified fields will get their default value.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Object fields that should be visible from outside the defining module have to be marked with *.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Tuples are very much like what you have seen so far from objects.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] They are value types where the assignment operator copies each component.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Unlike object types though, tuple types are structurally typed, meaning different tuple-types are *equivalent* if they specify fields of the same type and of the same name in the same order.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The constructor () can be used to construct tuples.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The order of the fields in the constructor must match the order in the tuple's definition.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] But unlike objects, a name for the tuple type may not be used here.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Like the object type the notation t.field is used to access a tuple's field.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Another notation that is not available for objects is t[i] to access the i'th field.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Even though you don't need to declare a type for a tuple to use it, tuples created with different field names will be considered different objects despite having the same field types.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Tuples can be *unpacked* during variable assignment.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This can be handy to assign directly the fields of the tuples to individually named variables.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] An example of this is the splitFile proc from the os module which returns the directory, name, and extension of a path at the same time.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] For tuple unpacking to work you must use parentheses around the values you want to assign the unpacking to, otherwise, you will be assigning the same value to all the individual variables!
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Fields of tuples are always public, they don't need to be explicitly marked to be exported, unlike for example fields in an object type.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] References (similar to pointers in other programming languages) are a way to introduce many-to-one relationships.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This means different references can point to and modify the same location in memory.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Nim distinguishes between traced and untraced references.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Untraced references are also called *pointers*.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Traced references point to objects in a garbage-collected heap, untraced references point to manually allocated objects or objects elsewhere in memory.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] However, for certain low-level operations (e.g. accessing the hardware), untraced references are necessary.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Traced references are declared with the **ref** keyword; untraced references are declared with the **ptr** keyword.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The empty [] subscript notation can be used to *de-refer* a reference, meaning to retrieve the item the reference points to.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] To deal with untraced memory, the procedures alloc, dealloc and realloc can be used.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The system module's documentation contains further details.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] If a reference points to *nothing*, it has the value nil.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A procedural type is a (somewhat abstract) pointer to a procedure. nil is an allowed value for a variable of a procedural type.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Nim uses procedural types to achieve functional programming techniques.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A subtle issue with procedural types is that the calling convention of the procedure influences the type compatibility: procedural types are only compatible if they have the same calling convention.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The different calling conventions are listed in the manual.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A Distinct type allows for the creation of a new type that "does not imply a subtype relationship between it and its base type".
[src:nim-lang/tut1] You must **explicitly** define all behavior for the distinct type.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] To help with this, both the distinct type and its base type can cast from one type to the other.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Nim supports splitting a program into pieces with a *module* concept.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A module may gain access to the symbols of another module by using the import statement.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The above module exports x and *, but not y.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A module's top-level statements are executed at the start of the program.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This can be used to initialize complex data structures for example.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Each module has a special magic constant isMainModule that is true if the module is compiled as the main file.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] This is very useful to embed tests within the module as shown by the above example.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] A symbol of a module *can* be *qualified* with the module.symbol syntax.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] And if a symbol is ambiguous, it *must* be qualified.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] But this rule does not apply to procedures or iterators.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The normal import statement will bring in all exported symbols.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] These can be limited by naming symbols that should be excluded using the except qualifier.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] We have already seen the simple import statement that just imports all exported symbols.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] The from statement can also force namespace qualification on symbols, thereby making symbols available, but needing to be qualified in order to be used.
[src:nim-lang/tut1] Since module names are generally long to be descriptive, you can also define a shorter alias to use when qualifying symbols.
[src:nim-lang/tut2] This document is a tutorial for the advanced constructs of the *Nim* programming language.
[src:nim-lang/tut2] Pragmas are Nim's method to give the compiler additional information/ commands without introducing a massive number of new keywords.
[src:nim-lang/tut2] Pragmas are enclosed in the special {. and .} curly dot brackets.
